"Sala M.M., Arrieta J.M., Boras J.A., Duarte C.M., Vaqué D.","The impact of ice melting on bacterioplankton in the Arctic Ocean",2010,"Polar Biology","33","12",,"1683","1694",,,10.1007/s00300-010-0808-x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78751585332&partnerID=40&md5=b4002ac8b778e82d791832d5abfdb175","Departament de Biologia Marina i Oceanografia, Institut de Ciències del Mar (CSIC), Passeig Marítim de la Barceloneta 37-49, 08003 Barcelona, Spain; Grup d'Oceanografia Interdisciplinar, IMEDEA (CSIC-UIB) Institut Mediterrani d'Estudis Avançats, Miquel Marquès 21, 07190 Esporles, Illes Balears, Spain","Sala, M.M., Departament de Biologia Marina i Oceanografia, Institut de Ciències del Mar (CSIC), Passeig Marítim de la Barceloneta 37-49, 08003 Barcelona, Spain; Arrieta, J.M., Grup d'Oceanografia Interdisciplinar, IMEDEA (CSIC-UIB) Institut Mediterrani d'Estudis Avançats, Miquel Marquès 21, 07190 Esporles, Illes Balears, Spain; Boras, J.A., Departament de Biologia Marina i Oceanografia, Institut de Ciències del Mar (CSIC), Passeig Marítim de la Barceloneta 37-49, 08003 Barcelona, Spain; Duarte, C.M., Grup d'Oceanografia Interdisciplinar, IMEDEA (CSIC-UIB) Institut Mediterrani d'Estudis Avançats, Miquel Marquès 21, 07190 Esporles, Illes Balears, Spain; Vaqué, D., Departament de Biologia Marina i Oceanografia, Institut de Ciències del Mar (CSIC), Passeig Marítim de la Barceloneta 37-49, 08003 Barcelona, Spain","Global warming and the associated ice melt are leading to an increase in the organic carbon in the Arctic Ocean. We evaluated the effects of ice melt on bacterioplankton at 21 stations in the Greenland Sea and Arctic Ocean in the summer of 2007, when a historical minimum of Arctic ice coverage was measured. Polar Surface Waters, which have a low temperature and low salinity and originate mainly from melted ice, contained a very low abundance of bacteria (7.01 × 105 ± 2.20 × 105 cells ml-1); however, these bacteria had high specific bacterial production (2.40 ± 1.61 fmol C bac-1 d-1) compared to those in Atlantic Waters. Specifically, bacterioplankton in Polar Surface Waters showed a preference for utilizing carbohydrates and had significantly higher specific activities of the glycosidases assayed, i. e. β-glucosidase, xylosidase, arabinosidase and cellobiosidase. Furthermore, bacterioplankton in Polar Sea Waters showed preferential growth on some of the carbohydrates in the Biolog Ecoplate, such as d-cellobiose and N-acetyl-d-glucosamine. Our results suggest that climate change and the associated melting of Arctic ice might induce changes in bacterioplankton functional diversity by enhancing the turnover of carbohydrates. Since organic aggregates are largely composed of polysaccharides, higher solubilization of aggregates might modify the carbon cycle, weaken the biological pump and have biogeochemical and ecological implications for the future Arctic Ocean. © 2010 Springer-Verlag.","Arctic; Bacteria; Biolog; Ectoenzyme; Functional diversity; Global change","abundance; bacterioplankton; bacterium; biogeochemistry; biological pump; carbohydrate; carbon cycle; enzyme activity; functional change; global change; growth rate; ice cover; organic carbon; polysaccharide; Arctic Ocean; Atlantic Ocean; Bacteria (microorganisms)",,,,,,"Alonso-Sáez, L., Vázquez-Domínguez, E., Pinhassi, J., Cardelús, C., Sala, M.M., Lekunberri, I., Unrein, F., Gasol, J.M., Factors controlling the year-round variability in carbon flux through bacteria in a coastal marine system (2008) Ecosystems, 11, pp. 397-409; Amon, R.M.W., Benner, R., Combined neutral sugars as indicators of the diagenetic state of dissolved organic matter in the Arctic Ocean (2003) Deep-Sea Res I, 50, pp. 151-169; Anderson, M.R., Rivkin, R.B., Seasonal patterns in grazing mortality of bacterioplankton in polar oceans: a bipolar comparison (2001) Aquat Microb Ecol, 25, pp. 195-206; Arnosti, C., Functional differences between Arctic seawater and sedimentary microbial comm